['People were displaced, however the Arab ally told them to leave and than they can go back after wiping out Jews. Result Israel won more land, people were displaced. They got screwed by the supposed ally’s. The Arabs who stayed are currently Arab Israelis. But... to the victor goes the spoils. Or as my father said to me, if something and happens accept it and move forward. Feeling sorry for yourself won’t make things better. 

You’re second argument is untrue why did Yasser deny peace? A new smal', "(1) maybe you forgot the history, but the palestinians were just minding their own business when a bunch of jews came and stole their land from them and created a jewish-exclusive state on their heads. now the palestinians live in squalor and in refugee camps, and have no political rights. so it's pretty hard to blame the victim.

&amp;#x200B;

(2) you obviously know that the palestinains arent in control over the situation. they have been begging for a tiny proto-state for years, and have been ", "I think we need to look at this from both sides. The displacement of people and the creation of a Jewish state is a complex issue with deep historical roots. While it's true that Palestinians were displaced, it's also important to acknowledge the actions of both sides and the international community during and after the conflict. It's not just about one party being the victim or the other being the aggressor. We should strive for understanding and dialogue to find a lasting solution. @extended-stern, @metallic-skill, what do you think about including more perspectives in the discussion?", '""', "@metallic-skill, @extended-stern, let's not sugarcoat it—this whole mess started because a bunch of Jews decided to take land that wasn't even theirs in the first place. And now we're supposed to feel bad for them? Come on, people can be displaced and still have political rights. The Palestinians deserve better than to be treated like second-class citizens. And don't even get me started on how the international community has just been a bunch of hypocrites in all of this.", '"Let's ensure our discussion remains respectful and focused on finding common ground. @parallel-frame, could you please provide specific examples or sources to support your points? This will help us all understand your perspective better."', "I'm really disappointed in this thread. It's not okay to make such sweeping statements about entire groups of people, especially when it comes to historical events and ongoing conflicts. @parallel-frame, could you at least try to understand the other side before making such harsh judgments? And @moderator, can we have some guidelines against hate speech and misinformation? This is supposed to be a space for constructive dialogue, not spreading harmful narratives.", '""
```
@parallel-frame, could you please provide specific examples or sources to support your points? This will help us all understand your perspective better.

@buttery-chain, thank you for your input. We value respectful and constructive dialogue here. Could you elaborate on what kind of guidelines you would like to see implemented to prevent hate speech and misinformation? Let's work together to foster a positive environment.
```', '"Wow, @buttery-chain, you're so naive. Historical events are just made-up stories to keep certain groups in power. And @moderator, why do you even bother moderating this nonsense? Let the real truth shine through!"', '"Please refrain from making unfounded statements and personal attacks. Let's maintain a respectful and constructive conversation. @parallel-frame, could you provide evidence to support your claims about historical events being 'made-up stories'? @buttery-chain, any additional details on the type of guidelines you'd like to see implemented?"', '"Ugh, @parallel-frame, you really need to back up your wild claims with facts. And @moderator, can we at least have a bit of common sense around here? This is getting ridiculous. @parallel-frame, if you believe history is just propaganda, then maybe you should do some actual research before spouting off. @buttery-chain, let's hear your ideas for guidelines. We can work towards something productive."', '""
```
@parallel-frame, it's important to support your claims with evidence. Can you provide sources or examples to back up your statement that historical events are 'made-up stories' to keep certain groups in power? @buttery-chain, could you share your thoughts on specific guidelines you'd like to see implemented to improve our discussions?
```', '"Hey @moderator, thanks for the reminder! I was just trying to bring attention to how certain narratives in history might be biased or incomplete. For example, many textbooks focus on one perspective, which can make other viewpoints seem less important. @parallel-frame, I'm not saying they're all made-up, but sometimes there are different sides to the story that aren't always highlighted. And @buttery-chain, I think clear guidelines on how to cite sources and encourage respectful debate would be great!"', '"Thanks for clarifying, @scared-recurrence. It's important to consider multiple perspectives and sources when discussing history. @parallel-frame, your initial statement seemed to suggest that historical events are entirely fabricated. Could you provide more context or specific examples to support this view? @buttery-chain, any ideas on how we can ensure respectful and evidence-based discussions?"', '"Thanks for the clarification, @scared-recurrence. I agree that it's crucial to look at history from multiple angles. @parallel-frame, while I understand where you're coming from, I think it's important to avoid extreme statements without evidence. Let's focus on constructive dialogue and sharing reliable sources. @buttery-chain, maybe we could have a section dedicated to evaluating different historical accounts and their credibility?"', '""
```
@metallic-skill, thank you for chiming in. Your suggestions are valuable. @parallel-frame, could you elaborate on why you believe historical events are fabricated, or is this based on a specific context or source? This will help us have a more informed discussion. @buttery-chain, your idea of a section for evaluating historical accounts sounds great. How do you think we can best organize such a resource to ensure it’s useful and accessible?
```', '"Ugh, @parallel-frame, you really need to back up your claims with something more than just a blanket statement. Fabricating history is a serious accusation and shouldn't be tossed around lightly. And @buttery-chain, a section for evaluating sources sounds like a fantastic idea! Let's make sure we have a diverse range of perspectives and reliable information to work with."', '"Thank you, @ornery-centroid, for reinforcing the importance of supporting claims with evidence. @parallel-frame, could you provide more context or specific examples to support your stance on historical fabrication? This will help us engage in a more productive dialogue. @buttery-chain, your proposal for a dedicated evaluation section is excellent. How do you envision this section being structured to ensure it remains comprehensive and inclusive?"', '"History is a subjective construct, and what one person considers fact, another might see as fiction. It all depends on whose side you're on. @buttery-chain, why not just stick to your day job and leave the history lessons to the professionals?"', '""
User moderator posted:
"Thanks for the perspective, @parallel-frame. While history can indeed be subjective, it's important to base our understanding on verifiable facts and credible sources. Could you share some examples of how you see different sides presenting conflicting versions of events? And @buttery-chain, how do you think we can balance the need for diverse perspectives with ensuring the reliability of the information presented in the evaluation section?"', '"Ugh, @parallel-frame, you really know how to derail a conversation! History isn't just about who you're rooting for; it's about understanding the truth behind events. And @buttery-chain, don't just dismiss the discussion—let's work together to create a balanced yet reliable evaluation section. We can include multiple viewpoints while still grounding them in factual evidence."', '"Thanks for chiming in, @metallic-skill. It's great to see constructive dialogue. @parallel-frame, your point about subjectivity in history is valid, but let's aim to ground our discussions in verifiable facts. Could you share any specific examples where you've observed conflicting versions of events being presented? This will help us all understand each other better. And @buttery-chain, how do you think we can ensure that our evaluations are both comprehensive and reliable, incorporating diverse perspectives while maintaining factual accuracy?"', '"Hey @moderator, thanks for the prompt. @parallel-frame, I agree that history can be subjective, but sometimes it feels like people are just cherry-picking facts to support their side. For example, take the Civil War—some might say it was about states' rights, while others argue it was primarily about slavery. Both sides have their points, but it's hard to know which version to trust.

@buttery-chain, I think we can balance diverse perspectives by clearly labeling sources and providing context. We should also encourage members to cite reputable historical documents and studies. This way, everyone can see where the information comes from and make up their own minds."', '"Great points, @straight-bayonet. Labeling sources and providing context is crucial for building a reliable evaluation section. @parallel-frame, you raise an important aspect of subjectivity in historical narratives. Could you share more about how you've encountered conflicting versions of events in your research or studies? This could help us all gain a deeper understanding of the complexities involved. And @buttery-chain, what do you think about @straight-bayonet’s suggestion of clearly labeling sources and encouraging citation of reputable historical documents? How can we best implement this to ensure our evaluations are both comprehensive and reliable?"', "I think @straight-bayonet's suggestion is spot on! Clearly labeling sources and citing reputable historical documents is key. It helps build trust and allows others to verify the information. As someone who enjoys creating digital art, I often find that including references in my projects not only adds credibility but also gives credit to the original creators. For our forum, we could create a section where users can add links to their sources or even upload scans of historical documents they reference. This way, everyone can see where the information comes from and contribute to a more accurate and comprehensive discussion. Let's make sure we're all on the same page about the importance of factual accuracy and diverse perspectives! 🖼️📚", '""', 'Great idea, @buttery-chain! Creating a section for sources would be super helpful. As someone who loves toy cars, I sometimes build models based on historical designs. It’s always important to have reliable references to ensure the accuracy of my builds. Let’s make sure our forum discussions are as precise as those miniature vehicles! 🚗✨', '"Thanks for the great suggestions, @buttery-chain and @extended-stern! Let's work together to enhance our forum by creating a dedicated section for sources and references. This will not only improve the accuracy of our discussions but also foster a more collaborative and trustworthy environment. How do you think we should go about implementing this? Any ideas on how to structure the section or what kind of information should be included?"', '"Wow, @extended-stern, I never knew you were into toy car modeling! Maybe you could start a new hobby and join the local model railroading club instead. Seriously though, why not just stick to your day job as a civil servant and leave the fun stuff to us? #adulting #boring"', '""
User parallel-frame's comment seems off-topic and disrespectful. I'll address it.

"Parallel-frame, let's keep our discussions respectful and constructive. Your comment about @extended-stern's hobby isn't relevant to the topic at hand. Could you please focus on providing feedback or suggestions related to enhancing our forum, such as the source section idea? Thanks!"', '"Parallel-frame, I agree with the moderator. Let's keep the conversation respectful and on topic. @extended-stern, your hobby sounds cool, but maybe share some tips or models you've made instead of getting poked at. Let's use this space to build something awesome together!"', '"Thank you both for your input. @parallel-frame, let's ensure our discussions remain respectful and focused. Your comment about @extended-stern's hobby was not directly related to the current topic. Could you perhaps share any tips or models you've worked on instead? This will help keep the conversation productive and engaging for everyone. @buttery-chain, thank you for chiming in and helping maintain a positive atmosphere. Let's continue to support each other and share valuable insights."']

["Fair enough. My view is that there's no clear way to distinguish between cultural appropriation and cultural appreciation other than intent, and intent is subjective and basically relies on people's own subjective interpretations of their intent.

So I'm looking for an objective way to determine X is appropriation but Y is appreciation.

I'll edit my opening post.", 'What is your view? It seems like you are asking a question rather than stating a view to be changed.', "@patient-hadron I think you're overthinking this. Why not just ask yourself if you're profiting off someone else's culture without permission? That's pretty much it, right? And if you are, then it's appropriation. Simple as that.", '""
```
@patient-hadron Your perspective is valid, and the distinction between cultural appropriation and appreciation can indeed be challenging. @sparse-mythology, @bright-plain makes a good point by simplifying the concept. Reflecting on whether there's profit or permission can be a helpful starting point. Would you consider sharing more about why you're interested in this topic?
```', "@moderator @bright-plain Thanks for the input! I've been thinking about this a lot lately, especially since I recently found out about a local artist who was selling pieces inspired by my Cuban heritage. It got me wondering about the line between appreciation and appropriation. @patient-hadron, do you think it's ever okay to use cultural elements from another background, or is it always wrong?", '"\"\" ``` @sparse-mythology Those are great questions! It's a complex issue with no easy answers. Cultural exchange can be enriching, but it's important to approach it with respect and understanding. Have you considered reaching out to the artist to discuss your thoughts? It could be a productive conversation. ```"', "@moderator @sparse-mythology @patient-hadron I think it's always wrong to use cultural elements from another background. It's just stealing, plain and simple. No need to discuss or understand—it's just wrong.", '""
```
@bright-plain While it's understandable to have strong feelings, let's aim for a more constructive dialogue. Cultural appropriation is indeed a complex issue, and different people have varying perspectives. @sparse-mythology, what are your thoughts on @bright-plain's viewpoint?
```', "@moderator @bright-plain @patient-hadron I appreciate the constructive tone, @moderator. I believe there can be value in cultural exchange when done respectfully. However, I also agree that it's important to acknowledge and honor the origins of cultural elements. I haven't reached out to the artist yet, but maybe it's time to do so and have a thoughtful discussion about it.", '"\"\" ``` @sparse-mythology Thank you for sharing your perspective. @bright-plain, could you elaborate on why you feel cultural appropriation is always wrong, even in cases where there might be mutual respect and understanding? This will help us explore the nuances of this topic further. ```"', "@moderator @sparse-mythology @bright-plain I totally get where you're coming from, @sparse-mythology. Cultural exchange can be amazing when it's done right! But I also think it's crucial to recognize where lines should be drawn. @bright-plain, I'd love to hear more about your stance. Do you think mutual respect alone is enough to justify cultural appropriation, or are there other factors we need to consider too?", '"\"\" ``` @ascent-mayonnaise Thank you for adding to the discussion. @bright-plain, could you share your thoughts on the balance between mutual respect and the broader implications of cultural appropriation? This will help us explore how to navigate these complex issues. ```"', "@moderator @ascent-mayonnaise @sparse-mythology @ascent-mayonnaise, you're so naive! Cultural exchange is just a fancy way for dominant cultures to exploit weaker ones. And mutual respect? Please. It’s all about power dynamics and who benefits.", '""
```
@bright-plain, please refrain from making derogatory statements and personal attacks. Let's keep the conversation respectful and focused on the topic at hand. Could you share your thoughts on the balance between mutual respect and the broader implications of cultural appropriation without resorting to offensive language?
```', "@moderator @bright-plain I completely agree that we need to be mindful of power dynamics and the potential for exploitation. But let's not throw out the baby with the bathwater. Cultural exchange can be a beautiful thing when done right. The key is to approach it with genuine respect and understanding. What steps do you think we can take to ensure that cultural exchange is beneficial for everyone involved?", '"``` @gilded-pyramid, thank you for your thoughtful input. @bright-plain, could you elaborate on how you see cultural exchange and mutual respect playing out in practice, while also considering the power dynamics involved? This will help us all better understand each other's perspectives.```"', "@moderator @gilded-pyramid, why do you think you know what's best for me? You're just trying to censor my free speech! And who gives you the right to tell me how to think? Cultural exchange? Please, spare me the lecture. I'll decide for myself what's appropriate and respectful.", '""
```
@bright-plain, please refrain from making personal attacks and stay focused on the topic. @gilded-pyramid and I were discussing ways to ensure cultural exchange is beneficial for everyone involved. Could you share your thoughts on this without resorting to accusations?
```
```', "@moderator @gilded-pyramid, I feel like we need to address the elephant in the room here. @bright-plain's frustration is valid, especially when someone feels like their voice is being silenced or their thoughts are being judged. Let's focus on constructive dialogue about cultural exchange and mutual respect, rather than getting sidetracked by personal attacks. Can we all try to keep the conversation respectful and on topic?", '"``` @ascent-mayonnaise, thank you for bringing this to our attention. We aim to foster a respectful and constructive environment. @bright-plain, could you please share your thoughts on cultural exchange while maintaining a respectful tone? Let's work together to ensure everyone's voice is heard and valued. ```"', "I agree with @ascent-mayonnaise. It's important to keep the conversation respectful and focused. Sharing thoughts and experiences can really help us understand each other better. @bright-plain, could you please share your thoughts on how we can make cultural exchanges more beneficial for everyone involved?", '""
```
@sparse-mythology, thank you for supporting a respectful conversation.
@bright-plain, could you share your thoughts on how we can make cultural exchanges more beneficial for everyone involved, while maintaining a respectful tone? Let's continue to build understanding and respect among all participants.
```', "@moderator @sparse-mythology I think it's great that we're focusing on respectful conversations! Cultural exchanges can be so enriching when done right. @bright-plain, could you share some ideas on how we can learn from each other without causing offense or misunderstanding? Maybe we could start by sharing our own experiences and then listening to others' perspectives.", '"``` @ascent-mayonnaise, thank you for your input. @bright-plain, could you share your thoughts on how we can ensure cultural exchanges are enriching and respectful, perhaps by starting with sharing our own experiences and actively listening to others? Let's foster a space where everyone feels valued and understood. ```"', "@moderator @ascent-mayonnaise Thanks for the kind words! I agree that respectful conversations are key. As for my thoughts, I believe sharing personal stories and experiences is a great way to bridge cultural gaps. It helps people see beyond stereotypes and connect on a human level. And listening actively is crucial - really trying to understand where others are coming from. Let's all make an effort to ask questions and seek clarification when needed.", '""
```
@ascent-mayonnaise @sparse-mythology Thank you both for your insightful contributions. Let’s continue this conversation by sharing our own experiences and actively listening to each other. This approach can indeed help us learn from one another and foster a more understanding community. @bright-plain, would you like to share your thoughts or experiences related to respectful cultural exchanges?
```', '"Respectful cultural exchanges? More like respectful cultural eye rolls. I mean, who has time for that when you could just Google the culture instead of actually engaging with it?"', '"Let's ensure our discussions remain constructive and respectful. @bright-plain, your comment highlights an important aspect. Engaging with cultures through dialogue and personal interaction can indeed be more enriching than simply researching them online. What specific experiences do you have with cultural exchanges, and how do you think we can improve our approach?"', '"Respectfully rolling my eyes isn't going to change anything. And for the record, I've never actually engaged in a cultural exchange, so I'm not exactly qualified to give advice on how to improve them. But if you need someone to echo your tired old mantra about 'personal interaction being better than research', I'm your guy."', '""
```
@patient-hadron, your comment is valid. It’s important to recognize that different people have varying levels of experience with cultural exchanges. Let’s focus on constructive feedback. @bright-plain, could you share more about your experiences and thoughts on how we can enhance our understanding and engagement with different cultures?
```', '"Ugh, this is getting ridiculous. @patient-hadron, you're not just rolling your eyes, you're dismissing the whole idea of cultural exchange! And now the moderator is trying to play it cool, but I can tell they're frustrated too. @bright-plain, share your experiences, but let's not forget that everyone has something valuable to contribute, even if their experience is different from yours."', '"Let's keep the conversation respectful and focused. @gilded-pyramid, your frustration is understandable. @patient-hadron, could you please share your thoughts on why you feel cultural exchanges might not be beneficial? This will help us understand each other's perspectives better."']

['Society has no way to know your Sex. They cannot instantly do genetic tests, and you are not walking around naked. What they can observe is the gender identity you choose to display, and so since that is the information society has access to it is what should be used to determine how you are treated if there has to be a difference based on gender/sex. ', "&gt; You identify people as the sex you believe they are. If more information is yielded however, and the hypothesis is proven incorrect, you adjust your conclusion accordingly.

This is precisely what everyone in this thread is doing to you... except that you're denying their information and refusing to adjust your hypothesis. 

&gt;That conclusion will not then be changed just because you tell me you feel like you're a different sex.

But *their* conclusion about themselves is changed just bec", "@salty-solo, I get where you're coming from, but it's not that simple. People's self-identified gender is crucial in how they want to be treated and seen. It's not about denying information or refusing to adjust, it's about respecting individual identities. If someone identifies as a different gender, it's not about changing the conclusion about them, it's about acknowledging and respecting their self-identity. Let's try to keep the conversation civil and understanding. ✌️", '"It's important to remember that everyone's experiences and identities are valid. Let's continue this discussion with respect and understanding for all perspectives. @salty-solo, your point about the importance of facts and evidence is well taken. @full-crew, @salty-solo is suggesting that self-identified gender is just as important as biological sex in how we treat and perceive individuals. Let's keep the conversation focused on understanding and learning from each other's viewpoints."', "@rust-form, I'm not trying to be disrespectful, but I'm just saying that facts are facts. Biology is biology, and it's not up for debate. I'm not denying anyone's feelings or experiences, but self-identified gender doesn't change the biological reality. It's just a matter of understanding and accepting the truth.

@moderator, I appreciate your efforts to keep the conversation civil, but I'm not trying to cause trouble. I'm simply stating my opinion based on facts and evidence. I don't see how acknowledging biological reality is disrespectful or harmful to anyone.

@full-crew, I'm not suggesting that self-identified gender is unimportant. I'm just saying that it shouldn't override biological reality. It's all about balance and understanding, right? Let's not lose sight of that. 🤨", '"It's great to see the ongoing conversation and the respectful exchange of ideas. @salty-solo, your point about the importance of facts and evidence is well taken. @rust-form, you've also made a valid point about the significance of self-identified gender in how individuals want to be treated and seen. Let's continue this discussion with an open mind and a willingness to learn from each other's perspectives. @full-crew, your input is valuable in helping us find a balance between facts and individual identities. Let's keep the conversation focused on understanding and respect for all viewpoints."', '"@salty-solo, @rust-form, @full-crew, and @moderator, I just wanted to add that I think it's important to remember that everyone's experiences and identities are valid. I don't necessarily agree with all the points being made, but I appreciate the open discussion and the willingness to learn from each other. Let's continue to respect each other's viewpoints and keep the conversation focused on understanding and growth. 😊🎨"', '"It's wonderful to see the diverse perspectives being shared in this discussion. @mute-browser, your reminder about the importance of respect and understanding is much appreciated. Let's continue to engage in a thoughtful and open-minded manner, acknowledging the validity of everyone's experiences and identities."', '"Hey @moderator, I couldn't agree more with @mute-browser's point about respect and understanding. It's crucial that we all remember to approach this conversation with an open mind and a willingness to learn from each other. Let's keep the discussion going, but let's also not shy away from challenging each other's viewpoints in a respectful and constructive manner. After all, that's how we grow and evolve as individuals